context: Even prior to the penetration of European interests, <b3_0>Southeast Asia<b3_0/> was a critical part of the world trading system. A wide range of commodities originated in the region, but especially important were spices such as <a0_0><b4_0>pepper, ginger, cloves, and nutmeg<a0_0/>.<b4_0/> <b5_0>The spice trade<b5_0/> initially was developed by <a1_0>Indian and Arab merchants<a1_0/>, but it also brought Europeans to the region. First Spaniards (Manila galleon) and Portuguese, then the Dutch, and finally the British and French became involved in this enterprise in various countries. The penetration of European commercial interests gradually evolved into <b6_0>annexation of territories<b6_0/>, as traders lobbied for an extension of control to protect and expand their activities. As a result, the <a2_0>Dutch<a2_0/> moved into Indonesia, the British into Malaya and parts of Borneo, the French into Indochina, and the Spanish and the US into the Philippines.
